description:
The DeBen (DBN) was an ancient Egyptian weight unit.

This was the first true "protocurrency" of our world. 

The  DeBen (DBN) and the ancient Egyptian economy was characterized by the barter system; commodities were bought and sold. Payments were made in the form of grain, meat and cloth rations. The standard basic wage consisted of ten loaves of bread and one-third to two full jugs of beer per day. 

Before coins started to circulate in ancient Egypt around 500 BC, there was a system of values based on weights of gold, silver and copper. Metal measured in units of weight known as deben (around 90 g) could be used to settle bills and to trade. 

Thus, DeBen is a unit of measure for the world to use in the Digital Age!
